[402.00088, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              is saved (see  \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m  below).   The  default\u001b[m\r\n              value  is \u001b[4m~/.bash_history\u001b[24m.  If unset, the com‐\u001b[m\r\n              mand history is not saved when a shell exits.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTFILESIZE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              The maximum number of lines contained  in  the\u001b[m\r\n              history  file.  When this variable is assigned\u001b[m\r\n              a value, the history  file  is  truncated,  if\u001b[m\r\n              necessary, to contain no more than that number\u001b[m\r\n              of lines by removing the oldest entries.   The\u001b[m\r\n              history  file  is  also truncated to this size\u001b[m\r\n              after writing it when a shell exits.   If  the\u001b[m\r\n              value  is  0, the history file is truncated to\u001b[m\r\n              zero size.   Non-numeric  values  and  numeric\u001b[m\r\n              values less than zero inhibit truncation.  The\u001b[m\r\n              shell sets the default value to the  value  of\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mHISTSIZE\u001b[0m after re"]
[402.000925, "o", "ading any start"]
[402.000945, "o", "up files.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTIGNORE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 1561 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[403.956886, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[403.957081, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              mand history  (see  \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m  below).   If  the\u001b[m\r\n              value is 0, commands are not saved in the his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory list.  Numeric values less than zero  re‐\u001b[m\r\n              sult  in every command being saved on the his‐\u001b[m\r\n              tory list (there is no limit).  The shell sets\u001b[m\r\n              the  default  value  to  500 after reading any\u001b[m\r\n              startup files.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mHISTTIMEFORMAT\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              If this variable is  set  and  not  null,  its\u001b[m\r\n              value  is  used  as  a format string for \u001b[4mstrf‐\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mtime\u001b[24m(3) to print  the  time  stamp  associated\u001b[m\r\n              with  each history entry displayed by the \u001b[1mhis‐\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mtory\u001b[0m builtin.  If this variable is  set,  time\u001b[m\r\n              stamps are written to the history file so they\u001b[m\r\n              may be preserved across shell sessions.   This\u001b[m\r\n              uses  the history com"]
[403.957092, "o", "ment character to distin‐\u001b[m\r\n              guish timestamps from other history lines.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 1597 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[405.186854, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[405.187452, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              tory  expansion  and tokenization (see \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below).  The first character is  the\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4mhistory\u001b[24m  \u001b[4mexpansion\u001b[24m  character,  the  character\u001b[m\r\n              which signals the start of  a  history  expan‐\u001b[m\r\n              sion,  normally  `\u001b[1m!\u001b[0m'.  The second character is\u001b[m\r\n              the \u001b[4mquick\u001b[24m  \u001b[4msubstitution\u001b[24m  character,  which  is\u001b[m\r\n              used  as shorthand for re-running the previous\u001b[m\r\n              command entered, substituting one  string  for\u001b[m\r\n              another  in  the command.  The default is `\u001b[1m^\u001b[0m'.\u001b[m\r\n              The optional third character is the  character\u001b[m\r\n              which indicates that the remainder of the line\u001b[m\r\n              is a comment when found as the first character\u001b[m\r\n              of  a word, normally `\u001b[1m#\u001b[0m'.  The history comment\u001b[m\r\n              character causes history  substitution  to  be\u001b[m\r\n           "]
[405.187472, "o", "   skipped  for  the remaining words on the line.\u001b[m\r\n              It does not necessarily cause the shell parser\u001b[m\r\n              to treat the rest of the line as a comment.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 1857 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[406.094836, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[406.097377, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       mands restored from the history file (see \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n       low), while the command number is the position in the\u001b[m\r\n       sequence  of  commands  executed  during  the current\u001b[m\r\n       shell session.  After the string is  decoded,  it  is\u001b[m\r\n       expanded  via  parameter expansion, command substitu‐\u001b[m\r\n       tion, arithmetic expansion, and quote  removal,  sub‐\u001b[m\r\n       ject to the value of the \u001b[1mpromptvars\u001b[0m shell option (see\u001b[m\r\n       the description of  the  \u001b[1mshopt\u001b[0m  command  under  \u001b[1mSHELL\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mBUILTIN\u001b[0m \u001b[1mCOMMANDS\u001b[0m below).  This can have unwanted side\u001b[m\r\n       effects if escaped  portions  of  the  string  appear\u001b[m\r\n       within  command  substitution  or  contain characters\u001b[m\r\n       special to word expansion.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mREADLINE\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       This is the library that handles reading  input  when\u001b[m\r\n       using  an  interactive  shell, unless the \u001b[1m--noediting\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       option is given at sh"]
[406.097544, "o", "ell invocation.  Line editing is\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 4007 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[406.890119, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[406.891196, "o", "...skipping...\r\n       command history (see \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m below)  for  lines  con‐\u001b[m\r\n       taining  a  specified  string.   There are two search\u001b[m\r\n       modes: \u001b[4mincremental\u001b[24m and \u001b[4mnon-incremental\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       Incremental searches begin before the user  has  fin‐\u001b[m\r\n       ished typing the search string.  As each character of\u001b[m\r\n       the search string is  typed,  readline  displays  the\u001b[m\r\n       next entry from the history matching the string typed\u001b[m\r\n       so far.  An incremental search requires only as  many\u001b[m\r\n       characters  as needed to find the desired history en‐\u001b[m\r\n       try.  The characters present  in  the  value  of  the\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1misearch-terminators\u001b[0m variable are used to terminate an\u001b[m\r\n       incremental search.  If that variable  has  not  been\u001b[m\r\n       assigned  a value the Escape and Control-J characters\u001b[m\r\n       will terminate an incremental search.  Control-G will\u001b[m\r\n       abort  an incremental search and restore the origin"]
[406.891208, "o", "al\u001b[m\r\n       line.  When the search is terminated, the history en‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 4642 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[407.601804, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[407.602274, "o", "...skipping...\r\n              all of the shell word expansions.  See \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below for a description  of  history\u001b[m\r\n              expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-expand-line\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-^)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform history expansion on the current line.\u001b[m\r\n              See \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m below for a  description\u001b[m\r\n              of history expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mmagic-space\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform  history expansion on the current line\u001b[m\r\n              and insert a space.  See \u001b[1m\u001b[7mHISTORY\u001b[27m\u001b[0m \u001b[1mEXPANSION\u001b[0m be‐\u001b[m\r\n              low for a description of history expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1malias-expand-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform  alias  expansion on the current line.\u001b[m\r\n              See \u001b[1mALIASES\u001b[0m above for a description  of  alias\u001b[m\r\n              expansion.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1mhistory-and-alias-expand-line\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Perform  history  and  alias  expansion on the\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manua"]
[407.602287, "o", "l page bash(1) line 4846 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[409.259941, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K              current line.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1minsert-last-argument\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(M-.,\u001b[0m \u001b[1mM-_)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              A synonym for \u001b[1myank-last-arg\u001b[0m.\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1medit-and-execute-command\u001b[0m \u001b[1m(C-x\u001b[0m \u001b[1mC-e)\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n              Invoke an editor on the current command  line,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 4851 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[409.656713, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[409.656788, "o", "              and  execute  the  result  as  shell commands.\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[1mBash\u001b[0m attempts to invoke \u001b[1m$VISUAL\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m$EDITOR\u001b[0m,  and\u001b[m\r\n              \u001b[4memacs\u001b[24m as the editor, in that order.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7manual page bash(1) line 4855 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
